# P4 Workflow

## Multi-Instance Workspaces

Changelists alone are insufficient isolation — P4 will silently reassign an opened file from one CL to another if a second `p4 edit` targets the same file within the same workspace. For full isolation, create a separate workspace per task. Workspace names follow the convention `<user>_<host>_<project>_<branch>-task-<slug>` (e.g., `dfrank_RGAP-MXL5113G09_chezmoi_main-task-xonsh`). Before creating one, check `todo.txt` for existing `@p4workspace` claims (`todo.sh list @p4workspace`). Record a `todo.txt` entry with:

- `@p4workspace:<workspace-name>`
- `p4changelist:<changelist-number>` — the primary CL for this task
- `session:`, `agent:`, `model:` — same convention as git

Example: `(B) Add xonsh P4 config +riot @p4workspace:dfrank_RGAP-MXL5113G09_chezmoi_main-task-xonsh p4changelist:98765 session:20260521T150000Z agent:claude model:claude-vertex/anthropic-claude-sonnet-4-6-default`

On completion: submit or shelve the CL, `p4 client -d <workspace>`, and archive the `todo.txt` entry to `done.txt`.

## Subagents in Pure P4 Repositories

A `worktree-write` worker can launch in a pure-Perforce repository with no `.git` directory. It can read files and use its granted non-mutating tools, including MCP, memory, and scratchpad. `write`, `edit`, and mutating Bash remain blocked because P4 has no equivalent of Git worktree write isolation.

A Git-worktree approval establishes the Git workflow and local-file-mutation trust boundary; it does not grant a separate external-service authorization. The `mcp-mutation-policy` denylist independently classifies P4 submits and Jira or Notion writes as mutating calls. Gateway management calls remain intentionally allowed even when connection or OAuth actions have side effects. The worktree guard permits recognized MCP mutations only for a validated `worktree-write` worker.

Perforce-native write isolation equivalent to Git worktrees is not currently provided.

## Submit Rules

- **Sync-before-submit**: Always `p4 sync` before `p4 submit`. Resolve conflicts with `p4 resolve -am` (auto-merge) before retrying.
- **Never modify unowned files**: If a `p4 sync` introduces build breaks from files owned by another team, do not edit or patch those files. Sync to a known-good CL; do not escalate to the team manually (log the CL range and move on).
- **No selective file syncs**: Do not cherry-pick individual files from a different CL to work around a broken build. Always sync the full depot path (`p4 sync <depot-path>/...@<CL>`) to maintain a consistent, reproducible workspace state. Partial syncs create invisible divergence from any known CL.

## Broken-Build Recovery

Check `.ugs/state.json` → `LastBuiltChangeNumber` for the last good CL. If unavailable, bisect with `p4 changes //project/stream/...@<OLDEST>,@<NEWEST>` + `p4 sync ...@<MID_CL>` + rebuild until the breaking CL is isolated. Sync the full depot path to the good CL (`p4 sync //project/stream/...@<GOOD_CL>`), rebuild, and log the breaking CL range to console.
